70
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:35,170
- What kind of bad manners is this? 
 - Scammers!

71
00:05:35,170 --> 00:05:37,460
How dare you talk to me like that?

72
00:05:37,460 --> 00:05:40,470
You guys cheated me first.

73
00:05:44,330 --> 00:05:46,550
You cheated the wrong guy.

74
00:05:46,550 --> 00:05:48,720
Come on!

75
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:51,240
Hey.

76
00:05:53,880 --> 00:05:55,260
The old geezer's screwing around again.

77
00:05:55,260 --> 00:05:57,850
I told you if you screwed up one more time, you're out.

78
00:05:57,850 --> 00:05:59,380
Why are you doing this to me?

79
00:05:59,380 --> 00:06:01,540
The guy wearing glasses had a hidden card.

80
00:06:01,540 --> 00:06:03,110
Look at the CCTV.

81
00:06:03,110 --> 00:06:05,790
Okay, I won't do that.  Please cut me some slack for the last time.

82
00:06:05,790 --> 00:06:07,840
Just once more.

83
00:06:07,840 --> 00:06:10,810
Let me go. Punks.

84
00:06:34,300 --> 00:06:39,060
What do people see, rainbows?

85
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:44,790
I am someone who used to kill and spare people with a pen stick (stab).

86
00:06:44,790 --> 00:06:50,110
Have you ever met someone with brains?

87
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:03,520
What is this?

88
00:07:16,370 --> 00:07:18,630
Why isn't it going up?

89
00:07:19,770 --> 00:07:21,510
So annoying.

90
00:08:30,930 --> 00:08:32,860
What is this about?

91
00:08:38,290 --> 00:08:40,870
Everything is burnt.  Burnt.

92
00:09:17,950 --> 00:09:21,080
- Is that a lighter? 
 - You startled me!

93
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:23,450
What does it look like? Anyway ...

94
00:09:23,450 --> 00:09:27,590
Jeez, with your dirty hands. What happened to your gloves?

95
00:09:27,590 --> 00:09:29,240
Hey.

96
00:09:36,100 --> 00:09:38,050
Is the car defective?

97
00:09:38,050 --> 00:09:40,720
It would cause a circus if it were recalled. (TN: Car manufacturer  would have to recall defective cars.)

98
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:44,500
I think it was suicide.

99
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:47,880
What did he kill himself with? There's no charcoal.

100
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:49,880
Isn't it all gone because it got burnt?

101
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:54,260
Charcoal fires leave a mark in a round shape.

102
00:09:54,260 --> 00:09:56,430
There must have been butane gas somewhere.

103
00:09:56,430 --> 00:09:59,500
It looks like he ate and slept in the car.

104
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:02,460
Didn't he have a house?

105
00:10:02,460 --> 00:10:05,710
He's going to be hard to identify.

106
00:10:07,420 --> 00:10:09,380
I can't smell anything.

107
00:10:09,380 --> 00:10:11,600
Smell?  What kind of smell?

108
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:14,770
If a fire were lit, there should have been a  combustible substance.

109
00:10:14,770 --> 00:10:18,620
If that was what happened, there would be a smell, whether it was gasoline or alcohol or something similar.

110
00:10:18,620 --> 00:10:20,400
If there was a fire, wouldn't it all dissipate?

111
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:23,730
If it were ignited with oil, it would smell like oil. If it were ignited with gas, it would smell like gas.

112
00:10:23,730 --> 00:10:27,420
Because what was left dissipated, it's not like the scene of a fire.

113
00:10:27,420 --> 00:10:31,870
Something went wrong. If you're done with your investigation, turn it over to the traffic investigation department.

114
00:10:34,090 --> 00:10:36,340
There's something strange.

115
00:10:37,150 --> 00:10:40,360
- You can't see the point of origin of the fire. 
 - What's that?

116
00:10:40,360 --> 00:10:45,280
Point of origin. Where the fire started or something like that. Point of origin.

117
00:10:58,260 --> 00:11:01,980
How many urgent burglary and rape cases are there?

118
00:11:01,980 --> 00:11:05,710
Seonbae! Are you sure this is a big deal?

119
00:11:07,150 --> 00:11:10,420
You're the problem! Every time we have a case

120
00:11:10,420 --> 00:11:13,100
the detective has doubts.

121
00:11:13,100 --> 00:11:15,920
But, like the team leader said, there must have been butane gas or something like it.

122
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:18,750
Look at this. So haphazard.

123
00:11:18,750 --> 00:11:20,680
It isn't butane gas.

124
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:21,790
What?

125
00:11:21,790 --> 00:11:25,840
There is no gasoline or charcoal for lighting coal briquettes. There isn't even any thinner here.

126
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:27,580
Then what is it?

127
00:11:27,580 --> 00:11:30,690
 Report of Fire Assessment Results

128
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:33,780
- There was no cause. 
 - What?

129
00:11:33,780 --> 00:11:36,240
There was no cause for the fire.

130
00:11:39,310 --> 00:11:42,780
 Report of Fire Assessment Results

131
00:11:53,360 --> 00:11:57,720
There is no such thing as something without a cause. We just haven't been able to find it yet.

132
00:11:57,720 --> 00:12:02,220
I guess that's true. You can't find things like cigarettes after they burn.

133
00:12:03,100 --> 00:12:06,660
Cigarettes catching fire? Does that make sense to you?

134
00:12:06,660 --> 00:12:10,170
As long as the cigarette can produce embers, it can burn. Why wouldn't it be possible?

135
00:12:10,170 --> 00:12:12,990
- Inside the car? 
 - Yeah. On the seats.

136
00:12:12,990 --> 00:12:17,570
Don't you think that the synthetic materials in the car ceiling and floor burn well if there is a spark?

137
00:12:17,570 --> 00:12:20,850
What? So a spark from a lit cigarette or something like that caused the fire?

138
00:12:20,850 --> 00:12:24,860
But I just sat there oblivious until my whole body burned?

139
00:12:24,860 --> 00:12:27,100
You could have been drunk and fallen asleep.

140
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:30,370
- I don't think that's what happened. 
 - Why not?

141
00:12:30,370 --> 00:12:33,530
You can't sleep while driving. The car was still running.

142
00:12:33,530 --> 00:12:35,270
Exactly!

143
00:12:39,460 --> 00:12:42,950
So did the car really just explode on its own?

144
00:12:57,590 --> 00:13:00,930
There is a saying that you burn on the way to hell.

145
00:13:00,930 --> 00:13:04,660
They say that the most agonizing death is to burn to death.

146
00:13:04,660 --> 00:13:08,580
I don't know. There are a lot of charred bodies out there.

147
00:13:08,580 --> 00:13:11,480
So, in the West, wasn't burning at the stake the worst execution?

148
00:13:11,480 --> 00:13:16,650
Burning can also mean purification. So it depends on your religion.

149
00:13:16,650 --> 00:13:21,460
But look at this. Combustion hematoma.

150
00:13:21,460 --> 00:13:25,600
When a person's skull heats up, it bleeds. 
  Combustion hematoma: bleeding that appears as a result of thermal rupture of the skull.

151
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:30,950
There is no subdural hemorrhage or skull damage. This isn't the type of bleeding that happens when someone is alive.

152
00:13:30,950 --> 00:13:32,470
How can you tell?

153
00:13:32,470 --> 00:13:35,050
There is a burn on the mucous membrane of the airway.

154
00:13:35,050 --> 00:13:39,460
That's a sign that flames were inhaled when the victim was still breathing.

155
00:13:39,460 --> 00:13:43,840
- Geez. 
 - Usually, someone who has burned will have thermal fractures.

156
00:13:43,840 --> 00:13:49,730
A thermal fracture happens when the body burns. It means that the heat has broken the bones.

157
00:13:49,730 --> 00:13:55,960
- The bones? 
 In those cases, it can be difficult to distinguish from a fracture that occurred earlier on when the person was still alive.

158
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:59,280
But look here.

159
00:14:04,660 --> 00:14:06,230
What is that?

160
00:14:06,230 --> 00:14:09,860
It means that the bones were broken and fused back together at the same time.

161
00:14:09,860 --> 00:14:12,070
Is this not a suicide then?

162
00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:18,490
Doctor. Is it possible for someone to suddenly catch fire on their own?

163
00:14:18,490 --> 00:14:21,320
You mean spontaneous combustion?

164
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:25,420
- There have been some cases where people have spontaneously caught fire and died. 
 - Aren't all of those cases in America?

165
00:14:25,420 --> 00:14:28,660
Is there a rule that it couldn't happen in Korea?

166
00:14:29,990 --> 00:14:34,190
Were the causes of those cases ever determined?

167
00:14:34,190 --> 00:14:38,310
Since it is an American issue, you should go ask an American.

168
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:43,440
 Central Police Agency

169
00:14:43,440 --> 00:14:46,170
 Eugene Hathaway
 Criminal Behavior Science

170
00:15:05,320 --> 00:15:10,160
Excuse me. Is this really a real case?

171
00:15:10,160 --> 00:15:14,970
In English, it's called Spontaneous Human Combustion. It's one of the most well-recognized mysteries.

172
00:15:14,970 --> 00:15:19,660
If it is a mystery, that means that we still don't know the cause, right?

173
00:15:19,660 --> 00:15:23,760
But the case you brought up. Is it different from this one?

174
00:15:23,760 --> 00:15:26,500
This is more like an explosion than a fire.

175
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:28,290
Explosion?

176
00:15:28,290 --> 00:15:30,600
Sorry I couldn't be of more help.

177
00:15:32,220 --> 00:15:36,730
Have you ever seen anything similar to this?

178
00:15:36,730 --> 00:15:39,110
In America I mean?

179
00:15:39,110 --> 00:15:40,590
I'm not sure.

180
00:15:40,590 --> 00:15:45,750
There was nothing in this car. No material that could feed the fire, and nothing as the point of origin.

181
00:15:46,990 --> 00:15:48,990
Is that possible?

182
00:15:48,990 --> 00:15:51,830
The people from forensics also don't know the cause.

183
00:15:51,830 --> 00:15:56,290
This is the first time we've had a case like this. It's not easy.

184
00:15:58,130 --> 00:16:04,790
It is odd. It's hard to draw any conclusion from just a picture.

185
00:16:08,460 --> 00:16:11,670
Can I visit the site in person?

186
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:24,960
You're here on assignment right? How long have you been here?

187
00:16:24,960 --> 00:16:27,040
One year.

188
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:30,510
But your Korean is really good.

189
00:16:30,510 --> 00:16:35,590
I hung out with a lot of Korean students, so I watched some Korean dramas too.

190
00:16:35,590 --> 00:16:38,540
Looking at you, it would seem like you've lived in Korea for most of your life.

191
00:16:38,540 --> 00:16:43,590
Since your last name is Hathaway, is your father an American?

192
00:16:43,590 --> 00:16:46,320
Both my mother and father are Americans.

193
00:16:56,600 --> 00:17:02,390
So, how did you get into the FBI?

194
00:17:03,030 --> 00:17:09,280
My major was Social Psychology and I saw something interesting after going to a lecture about serial killers.

195
00:17:09,280 --> 00:17:10,750
What was it?

196
00:17:10,750 --> 00:17:14,520
The room of a serial killer who murdered 14 people.

197
00:17:15,330 --> 00:17:18,650
What was interesting about that room?

198
00:17:19,620 --> 00:17:22,140
It looked exactly like mine.

199
00:17:56,060 --> 00:17:58,690
The car windows were smashed because of the blast.

200
00:17:58,690 --> 00:18:00,330
Look over here.

201
00:18:00,330 --> 00:18:05,660
If the car itself is the issue, the engine explodes and flames spread from one side to the other.

202
00:18:05,660 --> 00:18:07,760
But that isn't what happened here.

203
00:18:07,760 --> 00:18:10,420
Was there really nothing here?

204
00:18:13,290 --> 00:18:18,820
That's impossible. A fire can start from just an ember, but an explosion is completely different.

205
00:18:18,820 --> 00:18:21,490
There must have been something inside.

206
00:18:21,490 --> 00:18:25,420
By that do you mean that someone put something inside the car?

207
00:18:25,420 --> 00:18:27,190
Probably.

208
00:18:28,220 --> 00:18:31,560
To go as far as to use fire to kill someone?

209
00:18:31,560 --> 00:18:36,340
The fire probably served a specific purpose to the person who set it.

210
00:18:36,340 --> 00:18:39,660
- Purpose? 
 - There are two options.

211
00:18:39,660 --> 00:18:44,610
The first is to hide the scene. The second is to reveal it.

212
00:18:45,410 --> 00:18:49,550
Hiding it makes sense to me, but what do you mean by using fire to reveal the scene?

213
00:18:49,550 --> 00:18:52,590
Maybe they wanted the body to be found.

214
00:18:52,590 --> 00:18:54,270
Why?

215
00:18:54,270 --> 00:18:56,270
Well, for example, they could have wanted insurance money.

216
00:18:56,270 --> 00:19:00,270
Once a body is found, you can confirm that someone died and collect life insurance.

217
00:19:00,270 --> 00:19:05,130
Or you could manipulate alibis, you could set fires at a specific time.

218
00:19:06,220 --> 00:19:10,430
Whatever the case, the goal is clear. They wanted us to look at this.

219
00:19:10,430 --> 00:19:14,520
Like some sort of notice?

220
00:19:25,630 --> 00:19:28,530
Did you identify the victim?

221
00:19:31,140 --> 00:19:34,120
His name is Son Wan Gi. He was 65 and has been detained several times

222
00:19:34,120 --> 00:19:37,560
for drunk driving and committing violent acts while drunk.

223
00:19:38,450 --> 00:19:41,590
- What? 
 - This is Son Wan Gi's house, right?

224
00:19:41,590 --> 00:19:46,250
That person doesn't live here! How many times do I have to say this?

225
00:19:47,540 --> 00:19:49,760
This is the address listed for him though?

226
00:19:49,760 --> 00:19:52,800
  Lee Geon Yeong 
 National Police Agency

227
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,910
It's been a while since that man left.

228
00:19:55,910 --> 00:19:57,960
But why are you asking?

229
00:20:05,510 --> 00:20:08,180
So he reported his girlfriend's address.

230
00:20:08,180 --> 00:20:10,110
Can we trust her?

231
00:20:10,110 --> 00:20:12,740
He could have been here.

232
00:20:12,740 --> 00:20:15,330
Is there no CCTV here?

233
00:20:15,330 --> 00:20:17,260
- Geon Yeong, let's take a look around. 
 - Sure.

234
00:20:17,260 --> 00:20:20,240
I'll go right, you go left. Let's go!

235
00:20:20,240 --> 00:20:23,100
Seonbae, this way is longer.

236
00:20:23,100 --> 00:20:25,070
- Lee Geon Yeong 
 - What?

237
00:20:25,070 --> 00:20:28,390
You must be too comfortable at work these days.

238
00:20:28,390 --> 00:20:31,170
Seonbae, the way you talk is gradually starting to sound more and more like our team leader.

239
00:20:31,170 --> 00:20:35,090
Wait. Now that I look closer, you look like him too!

240
00:20:35,090 --> 00:20:36,800
Hey!

241
00:21:44,460 --> 00:21:47,360
Hey, where is he? Where did he go?

242
00:21:53,430 --> 00:21:57,450
It's obvious you're following me.  Good job.

243
00:21:57,450 --> 00:22:00,850
- Did you come here looking for Son Wan Gi? 
 - Huh?

244
00:22:02,180 --> 00:22:05,650
What are you? Are you hanging around someone?

245
00:22:05,650 --> 00:22:08,250
Damn. It was so hard for me to find this address.

